\begin_layout Subsubsection
Climate modes of variability
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Among the most important modes of climate variability for Australia are
 El Niño—Southern Oscillation (ENSO), the Southern Annular Mode (SAM) and
 the Indian Ocean Dipole (IOD) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Risbey2009"

\end_inset

.
 Improving the capacity to predict extreme bushfire seasons will rely on
 understanding how they are influenced by these large-scale atmospheric
 circulation variations.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
ENSO is associated with potentially dangerous bushfire weather in southeast
 and central Australia especially during El Niño events (characterised by
 positive SST anomalies in the central and equatorial Pacific Ocean); relative
 humidity, being the parameter most influenced by ENSO 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Williams1999"

\end_inset

.
 A positive phase of SAM (lower than normal pressures in the polar region)
 produces significant reductions in rainfall in southern Australia, including
 the south western tip of Werstern Australia, southern Victoria and Tasmania
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Risbey2009"

\end_inset

; which might have an influence in preconditioning bushfires in these regions.
 In Victoria, positive IOD events (warmer SST anomalies in the Western Indian
 Ocean relative to the east) are correlated with higher maximum temperatures
 and lower precipitation in spring (September-October-November, SON), exacerbati
ng fuel loads dryness in the bushfire season (December-January-February,
 DJF) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Cai2009"

\end_inset

.
 Finally, it has been demonstrated for this region there exists a potential
 to develop a forecasting tool to predict bushfire seasons based on climate
 variables that have a moderate relationship with ENSO 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Harris2013"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
ENSO has an important influence over bushfire regimes in several regions
 of the world (citations).
 For example, there is a link between El Nino events and decreased fire
 acitity in the Southern of the United States (citation).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Fire weather is influenced by ENSO in several regions in Australia.
 This influence is exacervated in the southeast when there is a superposition
 of the Interdecal Pacific Oscillation (IPO) and ENSO (citation).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Seasonal fire danger forecasting
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Seasonal forecasting uses statistical-empirical methods as well as dynamical
 models 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Doblas-Reyes2013,Troccoli2005"

\end_inset

.
 Statistical- empirical models describe the relationship between predictands
 and predictors usually assuming linear relationships.
 Common predictans are temperature and precipitation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Doblas-Reyes2013,Pepler2015,Troccoli2005"

\end_inset

.
 Usual predictors are sea surface temperature, soil moisture, snow cover
 and sea ice 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Doblas-Reyes2013,Troccoli2005"

\end_inset

.
 One of the most common problems with this approach is multicollinearity
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Troccoli2005"

\end_inset

.
 This occurs when several predictors are variables in the forecast and they
 are correlated.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Dynamical forecasts rely on the physical modelation of the climate system.
 A simple model describes the interactions of the atmosphere only.
 In complex models, all the components of the system and their interactions
 take part.
 Setting initial conditions and insufficient knowledge of physical processes
 are common problems with them 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Doblas-Reyes2013,Troccoli2005"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Dynamical models have in general better forecasting accuracy than statistical-em
pirical methods
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Doblas-Reyes2013"

\end_inset

.
 Additionally, ensemble dynamical models perform better than a single model
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Pepler2015"

\end_inset

.
 Yet, sophisticated statistical methods can have an accuracy comparable
 to the dynamical counterparts
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Doblas-Reyes2013"

\end_inset

.
 In practise, decision-makers use a combination of statistical-empirical
 and dynamical approaches 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Doblas-Reyes2013"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Variables that are usually forecasted are temperature and precipitation.
 The forecast for them is better for their mean values than the extremes
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Doblas-Reyes2013,Pepler2015"

\end_inset

.
 However, seasonal bushfire weather forecasting requires also information
 about relative humidity and wind.
 The skill to forecast this variables is less developed 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Roads2005"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In Australia, there is a relationship between fire activity and ENSO.
 Tasmania exhibits more area burnt with decreased rainfall in the coincident
 summer season
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Nicholls2007"

\end_inset

.
 Since ENSO is a major driver of Australian rainfall
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Risbey2009a"

\end_inset

; 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Nicholls2007"

\end_inset

 suggested its indices can contribute to forecast fire activity in this
 region.
 The Northern Territory exhibits a strong relationship between area burnt,
 rainfall and ENSO 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Harris2008"

\end_inset

.
 In Victoria, there is also potential to use ENSO indices for bushfire activity
 forecasting 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Harris2013"

\end_inset

.
 However, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Nicholls2007"

\end_inset

acknowledged that ENSO and fire activity could not have a link in other
 regions of the country.
\end_layout

