\begin_layout Subsection
Extended FFDI record
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The calcualtion of the FFDI was necesary to explore seasonal bushfire weather
 in Victoria.
 Especifically, the relationship between climate modes of variability, bushfire
 weather and bushfire occurrences.
 Therefore seasonal metrics fo the FFDI were used.
 The sum of daily FFDI values for the DJF season represents a seasonal bushfire
 weather metric.
 A second metric used was the number of days with a FFDI greater than 25
 for the same season.
 The calcualtions were performed using weather station data.
 Additionally, reanalysis data was also used after a linear scaling bias-correct
ion.
 All the calculations presented in this section represent average values
 in Victoria.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
FFDI calculated with weather station data demonstrated to represent Victoria
 with more extreme bushfire weather compared to the results using reanalysis
 data.
 This difference is likely to occur for several reasons.
 FFDI variables from renalysis data do not correspond exactly to surface
 values.
 Reanalysis data is available from 1000 h-Pa level.
 The FFDI with weather station data is calcualted with values at 3 pm.
 Yet, reanalysis data for FFDI variables is available on a 6-hourly basis.
 This limited the availability of data to 4 pm values.
 Finally, there are intricsinc limitations in the reanalysis dataset already
 discussed in Chapter 2.
 Yet, simple linear scaling tecniques demonstrated to adjust the biases
 without signifincatly altering the correlations.
 The bias-correction of each variable will be examined in this section.
\end_layout

