 This provided confidence that the rest of the correlations would reveal
 accurate insights about the relationship with the other variables.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The VSBI showed to be significantly correlated at the 5% level with the
 climate variables and with El Nino indices.
 This is an expected result that provided confidence of the correlations
 with the other variables.
 The VSBI in this season didn't show any correlation with the AAO index.
 However, it presented a strong, positive and statistically significant
 relationship with DMI.
 These relationship is stronger than the relationship with El Nino indices.
 Additionally, the VSBI is strongly correlated with the two metrics of FFDI,
 although the correlation is higher for FFDI(cum).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Correlations between El Nino indices also presented expected results.
 SST1.2 was negativelly correlated with SOI and positively correlated with
 NINO3.4.
 SOI was negativelly correlated with NINO3.4.
 Among these indices, NINO3.4, presented more statistically singificant results
 with the rest of the variables in comparision to other El Nino indices.
 The DMI index presented moderate to strong correlations with every variable,
 except with the AAO.
 The AAO index only presented a statistically significant (negative) correlation
 with temperature.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
